Advocacy groups say laws meant to protect them aren’t worth the paper they’re written on. eNCA’s Nobesuthu Hejana reports. Courtesy #DStv403 CAPE TOWN - Thirteen gay people have been killed countrywide since the beginning of the year because of their sexual orientation. Advocacy groups say laws meant to protect them aren’t worth the paper they’re written on. Sharon Cox from an organisation fighting for the rights of the LGBTQ+ community - the Triangle Project - says its high time government gets its act together to protect gays. READ: Motive for brutal murder of SAA flight attendant unclear In Cape Town in the past two months, hate crimes resulted in four deaths in Khayelitsha. While investigations are ongoing, the organisation believes less effort is being put into solving these crimes. * eNCA’s Nobesuthu Hejana reports.